S-task16.answer.value: I've found that the majority of accounts in this network are people not institutions. As well as the majority of accounts' continent of origin being in Europe. However the users with the most tweets and followers are located in North America and Asia. Robert and Jeffrey have the most edges and number interactions. Jon EVis19 Jason giCentre Noeska Alex Robert and Jeffrey are all apart of the largest cluster on the network in terms of interactions.
S-task16.prompt: Please explore the network freely and report on your findings. Is there anything surprising or particularly interesting in the network?
overallFeedback.overall: I loved both of the tasks. The visualization tool reminded me of some classes I took at BU during high school and also re-introduced me to social graph visualizations. Now I want to test out Neo4js. However I have to say I'd suggest logging the tasks during the test in a sequential step-by-step list for survey takers to follow. They may not be as familiar with data visualization as some of us are.
overallFeedback.training.explanation: The training videos were very useful in introducing me to graph-based visualizations and social graphs so when I was given the guide and training tasks I was able to overcome the learning curve a bit more easily than if I hadn't watched the video.

S-task16.answer.value: The person with the oldest account (Lynn) has very few interactions within the network but a relatively large number of followers and tweets. The institutions generally seem to have fewer tweets than the people but they also seem to be more likely to have a large number of followers in spite of having few tweets (with a few exceptions people with few tweets generally have few followers). It also seems that the European accounts seem to have more of a tendency to have few followers and few tweets -- maybe this suggests that Twitter is less widely-used in their countries?

overallFeedback.overall: Overall I found the matrix very interesting to use. At times I did not feel that I was using it properly but I did find it mostly easy to navigate and I think that I could become very comfortable using a matrix in this way if I were able to practice with it more. In general this seems like a very efficient way to display and examine data. The study was very enjoyable overall!
overallFeedback.training.explanation: I think it would have been helpful to have a few more rounds of practice before starting the tasks. Although some things were very clear and I figured others out as I went along there were some aspects of the matrix which I never really felt confident that I was using correctly.

One of my only complaints would be that sometimes the data popup bubbles when hovering with my cursor did not appear above the cursor but somewhere else. The font was also small. This is one of the more unique and stimulating studies I have participated in on Prolific and I am grateful that I could be a part of it.

overallFeedback.overall: Was a quite fairly interesting data ''game'' useful for teaching children in primary school etc. how strong social media is and the influence certain people can have. Basically you’re a node in a network. Of course that’s even more true now that we have social media. You’ll know a thousand people at least over the course of your life and they’ll know a thousand people each and that puts you one person away from a million and two persons away from a billion. And so that’s how you’re connected and the things you do is like dropping a stone in a pond. The ripples move outward and they affect things in ways that you can’t fully comprehend.
